FIND MAXIMUM NODE IN A BINARY SEARCH TREE (BST)

You are given a Binary Search Tree (BST). Your task is to find and return the maximum (largest) node value in the BST.

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains an integer N
N is the number of nodes in the BST

The next (N - 1) lines describe the edges of the tree
Each line contains three values:
pi ci Ri

where
pi is the parent node value
ci is the child node value
Ri represents the relationship
L means ci is the left child of pi
R means ci is the right child of pi

OUTPUT FORMAT

Print a single integer — the maximum node value in the BST

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ N ≤ 10000
1 ≤ pi, ci ≤ 100000
Ri is either L or R
All node values are distinct

SAMPLE INPUT

5
4 2 L
4 6 R
2 1 L
2 3 R

SAMPLE OUTPUT

6

EXPLANATION

In a Binary Search Tree, the maximum value is found by moving to the rightmost node. Here, the rightmost node is 6, so the output is 6.

class Solution {
    public static int maxNodeInBST(Node root) {
      Node curr=root;
      while(curr.right!=null)
      {
          curr=curr.right;
      }
      return curr.val;
    }
}



